            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p>[---]us Pius, son of Marcus, of the tribe Teretina</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it">
                <p>[---]us Pius figlio di Marco della tribù Teretina [---] sua madre</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" resp="#JP">
                <p>The surviving traces at the start of line two are most readily compatible in the context with TF, which would be <hi rend="italic">T(iberi) f(iliam)</hi> as the filiation of the honoured mother's name. The suggestion of De Miro to read <hi rend="italic">devote</hi> is less plausible. De Miro's suggestion to read <hi rend="italic">ter pius</hi> as 'thrice pius' rather than tribal and cognomen/epithet cannot be followed. The first part of the text continued on another block to the left. The interpunct after 'suam' in line 2 and the edge of the stone suggest this is the right hand end of the text. The layout could imply another line below on another block, perhaps containing the explanation for the honours. It has been generally assumed that the stone belongs to the so-called 'Oratory of Phalaris', which in turn was suggested by the excavator Marconi (1926) to be a heroon. The idea that it was a tomb or heroon, rather than a temple was firmly rejected by Wilson  (1990: 31 and 356 n.102). Campagna (2007) has however rightly questioned whether there is in fact any evidence for the association. The block is the same stone as the temple; it does however show no traces of the stucco which covers much of the exterior of the temple. The formulation of nominative individual and then accusative for the mother makes it more likely that this is an honorific (perhaps a statue base?) rather than a funerary inscription, albeit using the Greek accusative for the honorand (Latin would ordinarily use a dative) - this latter feature could either imply a Roman / Italian immigrant to the island or else a 'romanised' Sicilian. Honours of this sort for a woman in Latin epigraphy at this date are rare.
                    <!--?us Marci filius teretina Pius . . . matrem suam. Broken on left and right, block from a large monument (Marconi sugg's heroon), found prior to 1926, amongst the ruins to the east of the so-called 'oratorio of Phalaris', of which possibly the titulus. 46 x 146 x 36 cm, letters 9.5cm. Name of the ?deceased is in acc., in Greek custom. Two lines survive only. CIL, p.1096 (addenda tertia) comments on line 1, 'fueritne Teretina tribus Agrigentinorum, ignoramus'. Wilson, p.31 writes, 'the fragmentary Latin inscr. makes it certain that its (sc. the oratorio) dedicator was an Italian immigrant, but in architectural detail and in construction techniques this temple was indissolubly linked with local building traditions . . . The temple must be the work of a Sicilian architect working for a Roman patron, as was probably the podium temple of c.130 found in 1984 at M. Iato.' (which latter has also Latin tile stamps). In n.102 (p.356) Wilson rejects Marconi's view, followed by Griffo, that it must be a tomb or heroon; discusses dates suggested by others, including Torelli (in Guide Laterza 151-3) 197 BC, to link with Italian colonists in 197 (after Cic., Verr.II.ii.123 [Sicilian anyway, not Italian!]), but thinks this too early, opting for c.125-75 as 'more probable'. Date of temple is however difficult; early dates rejected on basis of letter forms of inscr. Columns were Ionic, with a Doric frieze. Marconi in NSc 1926:111 opts for a date for the inscr. of first quarter of C1 BC. Name of the dedicant missing. Marconi considers this a Heroon dedicated to a Roman matron! Observes that we lack any other evidence for the trib. Teretina in Sicily. NB Campagna very plausibly questions whether the inscr. has anything at all to do with the 'oratory' temple, prob. in fact a private honorific or funerary inscr.--></p>
            </div>
